<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="28" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,478,582]" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,478,504]" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. The group is characterized by the male fore coxa possessing a cluster of strong black setae that appear fused together resembling a thorn (
<figureCitation box="[656,730,517,543]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,254,1499,1523]" captionTargetBox="[360,1226,637,1476]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[360,1227,637,1476]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Campsicnemus gladiator, n. sp., male fore coxa, lateral view, showing cluster of setae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/185643/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">
Fig. 
<number box="[712,730,517,543]" pageId="3" pageNumber="28" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
). No other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[992,1171,517,542]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Campsicnemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[992,1171,517,542]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="28">Campsicnemus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
possess these “fused” setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
